message.content: A 'Calidris fuscicollis' is a small shorebird commonly known as the white-rumped sandpiper. It is typically 15 to 18 cm long and weighs between 22 to 45 grams. The bird has a mottled brown and gray plumage with a distinctive white rump. It has a short, straight bill and long, black legs. The species can be found in arctic tundra habitat and travels annually from North to South America during migration. They are known to feed on invertebrates such as crustaceans and insects. The white-rumped sandpiper has a high-pitched, chirping call.
